1 SECTION 3.2.(c) Appropriation. – There is appropriated from the General Fund to
2 the Community Colleges System Office the sum of one million dollars ($1,000,000) in recurring
3 funds beginning with the 2026-2027 fiscal year for the Short-Term Workforce Development
4 Grant Program.
5
6 PART IV. SEAMLESS POSTSECONDARY TRANSFER
7
8 INCLUDE NORTH CAROLINA INDEPENDENT COLLEGES AND UNIVERSITIES IN
9 COMMON DIGITAL TRANSCRIPT
10 SECTION 4.1. The State Education Assistance Authority, in consultation with the
11 Department of Public Instruction, the Community Colleges System Office, The University of
12 North Carolina System Office, the North Carolina Independent Colleges and Universities, and
13 the College Foundation, Inc., shall incorporate the private colleges and universities located in
14 this State into the common digital transcript developed pursuant to Section 8A.15 of S.L.
15 2023-134. No later than March 15, 2027, the Authority shall report to the Joint Legislative
16 Education Oversight Committee on the progress made toward this goal, including at least the
17 following information:
18 (1) Any additional steps to be taken for this purpose and a time line for completing
19 those steps and publishing the transcript to students enrolled at private
20 colleges and universities in this State.
21 (2) Estimates of any additional costs needed to expand the common digital
22 transcript to private colleges and universities.
23
24 EXPANSION OF POSTSECONDARY TRANSFER TECHNOLOGY
25 SECTION 4.2.(a) Findings. – The General Assembly makes the following findings
26 regarding the current state of postsecondary transfer technology at institutions of higher
27 education in North Carolina:
28 (1) Seamless postsecondary transfer and reverse transfer reduces barriers for
29 learners and aligns to statewide economic and workforce goals.
30 (2) The Current Operations Appropriations Act of 2023, S.L. 2023-134,
31 authorized and supported statewide postsecondary data and technology
32 initiatives to improve student outcomes, including transfer efficiency.
33 (3) Expanding technology to support the transfer of student credits among and
34 between institutions of higher education will reduce the time it takes for
35 students to earn a degree and reduce costs.
36 (4) Successful postsecondary transfer and reverse transfer is necessary to achieve
37 the postsecondary attainment goal established in G.S. 116C-10.
38 (5) Additional investment is necessary to scale and integrate technology
39 supporting seamless postsecondary transfer and reverse transfer.
40 SECTION 4.2.(b) Initiative; Administration. – For the 2026-2027 academic year,
41 The University of North Carolina System Office, in collaboration with the Community Colleges
42 System Office, shall expand the current initiative (Initiative) to accelerate the transfer of course
43 credits among postsecondary institutions of higher education using postsecondary transfer
44 technology. This expanded Initiative shall provide and improve technology at participating
45 institutions of higher education that will simplify the credit transfer process for students, advisors,
46 and the participating institutions. The expanded Initiative shall allow students to easily compare
47 credit transfer options, speed up student decision making, and streamline transfer planning and
48 progress toward degrees in a manner that reduces overall costs for students in the State.
49 SECTION 4.2.(c) Appropriation. – There is appropriated from the General Fund to
50 the Board of Governors of The University of North Carolina the sum of two million five hundred
51 thousand dollars ($2,500,000) in nonrecurring funds for the 2026-2027 fiscal year for the
DRS45527-NGa-141A Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 expanded Initiative described in subsection (a) of this section. The University of North Carolina
2 System Office shall use these funds to identify and develop programs to accelerate the transfer
3 of course credits among postsecondary institutions of higher education in accordance with this
4 section.
5 SECTION 4.2.(d) Report. – No later than March 15, 2027, The University of North
6 Carolina System Office shall report to the Joint Legislative Education Oversight Committee on
7 the Initiative, including at least the following information:
8 (1) The number and identity of institutions participating in the Initiative.
9 (2) The progress of each participating institution in the following areas, with data
10 disaggregated on the basis of income, race, ethnicity, and other demographic
11 characteristics, where available:
12 a. Enrollments upon transfer.
13 b. Credentials attained as a result of the successful transfer of credits.
14 (3) Recommendations to scale credit mobility and transfer technology statewide,
15 including identification of data system needs and opportunities to further
16 reduce the time it takes for a student to receive a degree and any other student
17 costs.
18
19 PART V. NC CAREERS ENHANCEMENT
20 SECTION 5.(a) Findings. – The General Assembly finds that (i) maintaining a
21 high-quality, up-to-date central platform to disseminate information on career exploration, career
22 planning, and alignment of education to career pathways to meet workforce needs is a statewide
23 priority, (ii) NC Careers provides such a platform, (iii) enhancing NC Careers is essential to the
24 effective implementation of the provisions of G.S. 115C-158.10, and (iv) it is necessary that the
25 State provide funds to the Department of Commerce to enhance NC Careers and its ability to
26 serve as North Carolina's premier workforce information and career navigation resource for
27 students, parents, educators, jobseekers, and career counselors.
28 SECTION 5.(b) Appropriation. – There is appropriated from the Information
29 Technology Reserve to the Department of Commerce the sum of one million five hundred
30 thousand dollars ($1,500,000) in nonrecurring funds for the 2026-2027 fiscal year to enhance NC
31 Careers in accordance with this subsection. Enhancements shall prioritize functionality that
32 supports individualized career planning, integration with programs of study and industry-related
33 credentials, information on licensure requirements as applicable, and use by career counselors,
34 advisors, and coaches embedded throughout a learner's experience across education and
35 workforce systems.
36
37 PART VI. NORTH CAROLINA COLLABORATORY TO EVALUATE AND REPORT
38 ON THE WORKFORCE ACT OF 2026
39 SECTION 6.(a) The North Carolina Collaboratory (Collaboratory) shall evaluate
40 the programs and initiatives established in Parts I through V of this act each academic year
41 through the 2029-2030 academic year. The Collaboratory shall report the results of its evaluation
42 to the Joint Legislative Education Oversight Committee by March 15 of each year through March
43 15, 2030. Each report shall include the following information:
44 (1) The total number of students and adult learners engaging with each program
45 or initiative established in this act.
46 (2) The total funds expended to implement, design, and operate each program or
47 initiative.
48 (3) The effects of the programs and initiatives in this act on achieving
49 postsecondary attainment and workforce outcomes.
50 SECTION 6.(b) There is appropriated from the General Fund to the Board of
51 Governors of The University of North Carolina for the 2026-2027 fiscal year the sum of six
Page 4 DRS45527-NGa-141A

